  <sect2>
    <title>Installation</title>

    <para>
      First, apply a patch to prevent a build failure when building with GCC 5:
    </para>

<screen><userinput>patch -p1 -i ../ncurses-&ncurses-version;-gcc5_buildfixes-1.patch</userinput></screen>

    <para>
      Don't install a static library that is not handled by configure:
    </para>

<screen><userinput>sed -i '/LIBTOOL_INSTALL/d' c++/Makefile.in</userinput></screen>

    <para>
      Prepare the package for compilation:
    </para>

<screen><userinput>./configure --prefix=/usr \
            --mandir=/usr/share/man \
            --without-normal \
            --without-debug \
            --with-shared \
            --enable-pc-files \
            --enable-widec</userinput></screen>

    <para>
      Compile the package:
    </para>

<screen><userinput>make</userinput></screen>

    <para>
      Install the package:
    </para>

<screen role="root"><userinput>make -j1 install</userinput></screen>

    <para>
      Many applications still expect the linker to be able to find
      non-wide-character Ncurses libraries. Trick such applications into linking
      with wide-character libraries by means of symlinks and linker scripts:
    </para>

<screen role="root"><userinput>for lib in ncurses form panel menu ; do
    rm -vf /usr/lib/lib${lib}.so
    echo "INPUT(-l${lib}w)" > /usr/lib/lib${lib}.so
    ln -sfv ${lib}w.pc /usr/lib/pkgconfig/${lib}.pc
done</userinput></screen>

    <para>
      Make sure that old applications that look for -lcurses at build time are still buildable:
    </para>

<screen role="root"><userinput>rm -vf /usr/lib/libcursesw.so
echo "INPUT(-lncursesw)" > /usr/lib/libcursesw.so
ln -sfv libncurses.so /usr/lib/libcurses.so</userinput></screen>

    <para>
      Finally, set the correct file mode bits for the shared libraries:
    </para>

<screen role="root"><userinput>chmod -v 755 /usr/lib/lib*curses*.so
chmod -v 755 /usr/lib/lib*form*.so
chmod -v 755 /usr/lib/lib*menu*.so
chmod -v 755 /usr/lib/lib*panel*.so</userinput></screen>

  </sect2>

